# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: commer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:commer/00-scale] "OO" describes models with a scale of 4 mm = 1 foot (1:76) running on HO scale 1:87 (3.5 mm = 1 foot) track (16.5 mm/0.650 in).
[src:commer/00-scale] This combination came about since early clockwork mechanisms and electric motors were difficult to fit within HO scale models of British trains, which have a smaller loading gauge than their European and North American counterparts.
[src:commer/00-scale] A solution was to enlarge the scale of the model to 4 mm to the foot but keep the 3.5 mm to the foot gauge track.
[src:commer/00-scale] This also allowed more space to model the external valve gear.
[src:commer/00-scale] The resulting HO track gauge of 16.5 mm represents 4 feet 1.5 inches at 4 mm to the foot scale, which is 7 inches too narrow or approximately 2.33 mm too narrow in the model.
[src:commer/00-scale] In 1932, the Bing company collapsed, but the Table Railway continued to be manufactured by the new Trix company.
[src:commer/00-scale] Trix decided to use the new HO standard, being half of French 0 gauge (1:43.5 scale).
[src:commer/00-scale] In 1938, the Meccano Company launched a new range of OO models under the trade name of Hornby Dublo.
[src:commer/00-scale] The combination of 4 mm scale and 16.5 mm gauge has remained the UK's most popular scale and gauge ever since.
[src:commer/00-scale] In the United States, Lionel Corporation introduced a range of OO models in 1938.
[src:commer/00-scale] Soon other companies followed but it did not prove popular and remained on the market only until 1942, when Lionel train production was shut down due to wartime restrictions to the use of steel.
[src:commer/00-scale] OO gauge was quickly eclipsed by the better-proportioned HO scale.
[src:commer/00-scale] The Lionel range of OO used 19 mm (3⁄4 inch) track gauge, equating to 57 inches or 4 ft 9 in – very close to the 4 ft 81⁄2 in of standard gauge.
[src:commer/00-scale] There is a small following of American OO scale today.
[src:commer/00-scale] OO remains the most popular scale for railway modelling in Great Britain due to a ready availability of ready-to-run stock and starter sets.
[src:commer/00-scale] Ready-to-run in the UK is dominated by Hornby Railways and Bachmann Branchline.
[src:commer/00-scale] Other sources of ready-to-run rolling stock or locomotives include Dapol, Heljan, Peco, ViTrains, Rapido Trains UK, Accurascale, and previously Lima, Tri-ang Railways, and Mainline Railways.
[src:commer/00-scale] Other scales, with the possible exception of N, lack the variety and affordability of UK ready-to-run products.
[src:commer/00-scale] 16.5 mm (0.65 in) gauge at 4 mm:1 foot means that the scale gauge represents 4 ft 1+1⁄2 in (1,257 mm), 7 inches (178 mm) narrower than the prototype 4 ft 8+1⁄2 in (1,435 mm).
[src:commer/00-scale] This difference is particularly noticeable when looking along the track.
[src:commer/00-scale] As the market for proprietary track is mostly for HO scale, sleeper size and spacing are designed for HO and are therefore underscale.
[src:commer/00-scale] OO is also used to represent the 5 ft 3 in (1,600 mm) Irish gauge, where it is a scale 13+1⁄2 inches (343 mm) too narrow.
[src:commer/00-scale] Though they run on the same track, OO gauge and HO gauge models of the same prototype do not sit well together since the OO models are larger than the HO equivalent.
[src:commer/00-scale] These differences have led to the development of the finescale standards of EM gauge and P4 standards.
[src:commer/00-scale] Nevertheless, it is possible to model using OO to standards that fall just short of finescale.
[src:commer/00-scale] Overhang from long vehicles means that the normal separation between track centres are overscale to prevent collisions on curves between stock on adjacent lines, at up to 65 mm (for set-track (reduced down to 50 mm for Peco Streamline)).
[src:commer/00-scale] Overscale wheel width and deep wheel flanges are used on typical models (but particularly older models), and these require overscale rail profile and much larger clearances on pointwork than is prototypical.
[src:commer/00-scale] Pointwork is often compressed in length to save space.
[src:commer/00-scale] Many experienced modellers find the OO standard produces a "narrow gauge" appearance when the model is viewed head on.
[src:commer/00-scale] Greater accuracy is possible using either EM gauge or the closer-to-exact scale P4 track.
[src:commer/00-scale] Kits for doing this are also available from the aforementioned sources amongst others.
[src:commer/00-scale] Several of these kits are also available to the OO modeller who aims for more realistic track since most RTR track is actually scaled to HO and does not represent any British prototype, and the sleeper spacing is too close for scale.
[src:commer/00-scale] EM gauge has slightly overscale flanges and flangeways on point and crossing work; P4 is closer to scale but the smaller flanges and flangeways on P&C work expose poor track construction.
[src:commer/abbey-automobile] The **Abbey** was a short-lived friction drive car assembled by the Abbey Auto Engineering Co.
[src:commer/abbey-automobile] It used a 10.8 hp 1498 cc Coventry-Simplex engine.
[src:commer/abbey-automobile] It was built in 1922 only and cost £315.
[src:commer/abbey-automobile] It also had Marles steering gear and friction drive.
[src:commer/abbey-automobile] After 1922 the car may have been sold as the Lewis.
[src:commer/abbey-panels] In 2002 the company stopped much of its manufacturing and began a phased closure of the Abbey Panels plant in Coventry.
[src:commer/abbey-panels] They continued to run their aerospace engineering and machining company for some time, and refocused their efforts on redeveloping their industrial properties.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] AER offers a wide variety of technical services for customers, including design and analysis, manufacturing, engine assembly and testing.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] AER also provides a full package of engineers and personnel for race weekend support as well as electronics through their LifeRacing sister company.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] LifeRacing develops its own hardware and software including electronic engine controls (ECU), drive-by-wire controllers, and ancillary electronics and has aerospace contracts in addition to its racing activities.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] AER has experience in a variety of engine technologies, with particular expertise in racing turbocharged engines.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] CATIA V5 is used for all component design work and there is an in-house prototyping machine shop with 5 axis machining and transient dynamometer equipment for engine testing.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The company was founded with an accent on its electronic capabilities to allow it to develop engines of a more sophisticated level for manufactures.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] This merging of electronic and mechanical aspects of engine design led to their first contract in 1997 with Nissan for British Touring Car engines.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] Since 1997, AER has developed a number of different engine families for customers.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The engine was also used in the Crawford Racing Nissans in the Swedish Touring Car Championship, taking the title in 2000 with Tommy Rustad.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] With the demise of Supertouring, the AER-tuned SR20 was used in the short-lived World Series Light, a junior division to the Nissan World Series.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The AER P25 3.5 liter V6 is based on the production Nissan VQ35 engine as found in the Nissan 350Z.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] It was extensively re-engineered, originally for use in the Nissan World Series.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The changes include a bespoke dry sump conversion, pistons, connecting rods, crankshaft, camshafts and valve gear.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The P25 is used in single seat and sportscar applications with power output to 500 HP.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The AER P14 is a V6 engine developed from a production Nissan VQ engine.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The P14 was homologated for use in sportscars fitting in the SR2 category of the FIA Sportscar Championship.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] Engines in this series were required to be at a maximum of 3.0 liters and based on production units.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] Created in 2000, the P03 was AER's first clean sheet engine and was developed for MG/Rover for their Le Mans racing efforts.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] When they backed away from their Le Mans effort after a year, AER took the engine and developed it into a customer engine, the **P07**.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The P07 was a 2.0 liter inline-4 with a single Garrett turbocharger, producing over 500 HP initially and 550 HP by 2003.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The engine ran strongly through 2007 in the American Le Mans Series and Le Mans Series, as well as the 24 Hours of Le Mans, in the LMP2 class.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] In 2003, Dyson Racing took the ALMS P2 team and driver's (Chris Dyson) championships with their AER-powered MG-Lola EX257.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] Launched in 2006, the new P32T helped AER move to the top of Le Mans Prototype racing.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The P32T V8 engine was a bespoke AER design for LMP1 racing and was a 75 degree twin-turbo V8 originally built as a 3.6 liter in 2006 and 2007 and upgraded to 4.0 liters in 2008, called the **P32C**.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] Two Garrett turbochargers helped the engine put out more than 650 HP.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] A naturally aspirated variant, the **P32**, was designed with a range of 3.4 – 4.2 liters with the 3.4 liter designed for the 2011 LMP1 rules package.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The P32T engine project sprang from a conversation Dyson Racing had with AER and during its first season was reliable and quick, winning numerous pole positions.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] It ran in LMP1 cars competing at the 24 Hours of Le Mans, the ELMS and ALMS.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The engine was designed to take on Audi’s LMP1 3.6 liter twin turbo and its clean sheet design set new standards for size and weight using Formula One technology and weighed only 114 kg.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] Dyson Racing in America and Chamberlain-Synergy Motorsport in Europe initially used the P32T in 2006, while in 2007 Courage Compétition became a customer while Team Cytosport ran Dyson's former AER-powered prototype.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] In 2008, Intersport Racing ran the engine in their ALMS LMP1 entries and in 2009 and 2010, both Intersport Racing and Autocon ran the AER engine in ALMS P1.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The P41 was the first Mazda engine that AER had developed, which was accomplished in conjunction with Mazdaspeed for use in LMP2.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] An in-line four-cylinder single-turbocharged 2.0 liter, the MZR-R was debuted by B-K Motorsports at the 2007 12 Hours of Sebring, and B-K ran it through 2008.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] Dyson Racing took up the Mazda flag in 2009.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The four-cylinder P41 was based on the structure of AER's 3.6 liter twin-turbo P32T V8 engine.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] In 2010 the P41 was replaced with the new P70 with a new block and cylinder head and increased power for use in LMP1.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The engine represented the state of the art in turbocharged engine technology and was designed for the rigors of a 24-hour race.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] It is the smallest engine in LMP1, but on a per cylinder basis, the engine produces more power than a Formula One engine.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] In 2011, Dyson Racing swept the championship table in the ALMS P1 category with driver, team and manufacturer championships.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] Dyson Racing continues to run the engine and for 2013, the engine has been upgraded for wider power and torque curves and is called the P90.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The MZR-R was selected to power the new Indy Lights car that will debut in 2015, it will be badged as a Mazda engine.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The P60 was introduced in 2014, in response to new LMP1 regulations brought forth by the Automobile Club de l'Ouest (ACO) for the FIA World Endurance Championship.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] It was designed with the goal of high efficiency fuel consumption at the forefront.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The V6, twin-turbocharged engine has a displacement of 2.0 litres with direct fuel injection and a Life Racing engine control unit.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The P60 made its debut in the Kodewa CLM P1/01 at the 2014 6 Hours of Circuit of the Americas.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The following year, the engine was also used in the Rebellion Racing Rebellion R-One.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] Following the reveal of the SMP Racing BR Engineering BR1 for the 2018–19 FIA World Endurance Championship season, AER announced an updated version, called the **P60B**.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] The engine includes updates to the high-pressure fuel system, cylinder head casting, scavenge system/oil tank, ignition system and engine calibration, while also increasing displacement to 2.4 litres.
[src:commer/advanced-engine-research] For the 2019–20 FIA World Endurance Championship season, the Team LNT Ginetta G60-LT-P1, was fitted with an upgraded engine focusing on reliability, called the **P60C**.
[src:commer/agricultural-engineers-association] The AEA was established in 1875 to promote the commercial, technical and trade interests of British manufacturers and suppliers of agricultural machinery and celebrated its 125th anniversary in London on 18 April 2000.
[src:commer/agricultural-engineers-association] It was incorporated in 1955 as private company limited by guarantee without share capital.
[src:commer/agricultural-engineers-association] It now also champions the cause of manufacturers of outdoor power equipment and its current members cover a broad spectrum of manufacturers of land based equipment.
[src:commer/agricultural-engineers-association] The AEA issues trade statistics and commentary for the national media and organises large events for the industry such as Tillage Live, an annual UK cultivations event focusing on all aspects of crop establishment, and ScotGrass, a triennial grassland event.
[src:commer/agricultural-engineers-association] The AEA became a member of the Engineering and Machinery Alliance, UK, in 2010.
[src:commer/ats-euromaster] At its peak, the company had around 525 service centres, this was sometime in the nineties and since then it has continued to close non profitable service centres with a view to reopen at more strategic locations.
[src:commer/ats-euromaster] Euromaster made a structured wind down of its UK ATS Euromaster operation and ceased operations on 01 May 2026 after 60 years.
[src:commer/ats-euromaster] ATS operates a number of centres equipped for both car and van MOTs and servicing.
[src:commer/awd-trucks] In 1986, General Motors decided to sell their Bedford heavy-duty truck division to David J.B.
[src:commer/awd-trucks] Brown, who was the founder of Artix Limited, while they re-formed the Bedford light truck division into IBC Vehicles.
[src:commer/awd-trucks] The now-called AWD Trucks were mostly made for the export market, on which they were very popular, but in Britain, they were only bought by the construction industry and the military.
[src:commer/awd-trucks] At that time Brown opened a new firm called *Multidrive Vehicles* that built 8x6 versions of the AWD TK and AWD TL, mostly for the military and special services.
[src:commer/awd-trucks] By that time the AWD company had achieved £3 billion of exports and gained 4 Queen's Awards to Industry, with an annual turnover of £400 million.
[src:commer/awd-trucks] Brown sold the Multidrive Vehicles company to Caterpillar.
[src:commer/awd-trucks] Brown then became a design consultant for the Cat 7 Series ADT.
[src:commer/awd-trucks] The Bedford trucks that were built by Multidrive Vehicles, were modernized, re-skinned, and were re-badged to Caterpillar vehicles.
[src:commer/awd-trucks] These Caterpillar trucks were exported to many countries and were also used in the Gulf War, in Bosnia, Kosovo, and in other countries.
[src:commer/awd-trucks] The company re-entered the British market in 2001, and also started exports to South Africa that same year.
[src:commer/awd-trucks] In 2003 the company started producing a whole new range of military vehicles, but the production of the older trucks did not stop.
[src:commer/awd-trucks] With the death of Brown in 2006, the company was bought by Dr Qu Li.
[src:commer/commer] This business belonged to Commercial Cars Limited, a company incorporated in September 1905 by directors H.
[src:commer/commer] Underdown, barrister and director of Direct United States Cable Co with H.
[src:commer/commer] Hutchinson a director of Royal Exchange Assurance to manufacture: commercial cars, omnibuses, charabancs, fire engines and every kind of industrial vehicle.
[src:commer/commer] In 1920, it was described as the first company to specialise in the manufacture of internal combustion industrial commercial vehicles.
[src:commer/commer] In order to go into volume production a site was bought in September 1905 at Biscot Road, Biscot, Luton.
[src:commer/commer] Construction of extensive new workshops began on the five-acre site which was mostly complete by late 1906.
[src:commer/commer] Commercial Cars became a member of the Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders in August 1906.
[src:commer/commer] It was one of the first manufacturers of commercial vehicles in the United Kingdom, its speciality being the *Commer Car*.
[src:commer/commer] At Olympia's Commercial Motor Show in March 1907, Commer exhibited a motor-bus chassis with a 30–36 horsepower engine and a gearbox invented by Mr Linley, the works manager.
[src:commer/commer] Dog-clutches made the change rather than the spur wheels which remained in constant mesh.
[src:commer/commer] As well as the bus chassis Commer displayed a char-a-banc for thirty passengers and delivery vans being run by a substantial enterprise.
[src:commer/commer] A new "large and powerful" lorry, E43, registration BM 787, took part in the Great Commercial Motor Trials in September 1907.
[src:commer/commer] It also had a constant mesh gearbox (Comer (sic) slogan—'dogs which bite with a click').
[src:commer/commer] Unladen weight was (3.7 tonnes) 3 tons 13 cwt, the engine had four-cylinders, its output was 33 horsepower at 800 rpm.
[src:commer/commer] It had four forward speeds and was driven by side chains.
[src:commer/commer] Length 20 feet (6 metres), width just over (2.1 metres) seven feet and height (1.76 metres) two inches under six feet.
[src:commer/commer] The platform was (3.6 metres) twelve feet long.
[src:commer/commer] The newspaper noted that a *Commercars* "chassis" was transporting passengers at Widnes.
[src:commer/commer] Production of the first truck, the 3-ton *RC* type started in 1907.
[src:commer/commer] This was later modernized into the *SC* and so on through the *YC* range, which was also known as the "Barnet" series of trucks.
[src:commer/commer] With the outbreak of the First World War the factory turned to the manufacture of military vehicles for the British Army, and by 1919 more than 3,000 had been made.
[src:commer/commer] Though obliged to undergo financial restructure in 1920 in the hope of avoiding creditors, the business was unable to avoid repayment of a debt of £75,000 due to the Treasury, raised in order to pay 60 per cent Excess Profits Duty on wartime activities.
[src:commer/commer] Eventually, after agreeing terms with the Receiver in 1925, Commer was bought in 1926 by Humber.
[src:commer/commer] In 1931 Humber became a 60-percent-owned subsidiary of the Rootes Group.
[src:commer/commer] The Commer name was replaced by the Dodge name during the 1970s, following the takeover of Rootes by Chrysler Europe.
[src:commer/commer] After Peugeot purchased Chrysler Europe in 1978, the Commer factory was run in partnership with the truck division of Renault, Renault Trucks.
[src:commer/commer] For some time, it continued to produce the Dodge commercial truck range with Renault badges, and there was a small amount of product development.
[src:commer/commer] Eventually, Dodge production was cancelled in favour of mainstream Renault models, and there was a switch to the production of Renault truck and bus engines in the early 1990s.
[src:commer/commer] Many Commer vans and lorries are notable for being fitted with the Rootes TS3 engine, a two-stroke diesel three-cylinder horizontally opposed piston engine, which came to be known as the "Commer Knocker" owing to the distinct noise it produced.
[src:commer/commer] Newer Commer vehicles had Perkins and Cummins diesel engines, and, less commonly, Mercedes diesel engines.
[src:commer/commer] The N-series was introduced in 1935, and was also used by the British armed forces in World War II.
[src:commer/commer] Production was halted in 1939 and was not recommenced after the war.
[src:commer/commer] Cab-over and bonneted trucks were both available, fitted with petrol or diesel engines.
[src:commer/commer] The six-cylinder petrol engine was available in 3,181 cc (194.1 cu in) or 4,086 cc (249.3 cu in) versions.
[src:commer/commer] The Perkins Leopard diesel engine was also available.
[src:commer/commer] The range included N as well as the lighter-duty LN range of trucks (numbered N1 through N6 depending on their approximate weight capacities in tons), as well as the PN-series of buses, commonly fitted with diesels.
[src:commer/commer] There was also the 4/5 ton PLNF5 introduced in 1938.
[src:commer/commer] The LN was officially capable of carrying weights similar to those of the corresponding N-series trucks, but had a lower overall max weight and was "definitely not intended to carry an overload" – a tacit recognition of British truckers' habitual overloading of their trucks.
[src:commer/commer] The LN-range was also designed to operate effectively within the 1930s 30 mph speed limit for heavier lorries.
[src:commer/commer] After the introduction of the 4/5-ton LN5, the 5+1⁄2-ton (5,600 kg) N5 was discontinued.
[src:commer/commer] However, the market decreed otherwise and the N5's revival was announced in February 1938.
[src:commer/commer] The Commer Superpoise range (Q-series) was introduced in 1939, with both semi-forward and full-forward control options.
[src:commer/commer] These newer models were more streamlined and modern in appearance and adopted an American International-like front end.
[src:commer/commer] The line included trucks of 1+1⁄2 to six tons capacity powered by 6-cylinder petrol or diesel engines.
[src:commer/commer] A new Superpoise range (QX-series, although QX had also been used on some earlier Superpoises) with payloads of between two and five tons was introduced in 1955.
[src:commer/commer] The truck proved fairly popular but did not provide fierce competition for products by more known brands such as Leyland and Bedford.
[src:commer/commer] Even though Commer was not purchased by Chrysler until 1967, the British Dodge 200 series (the successor to the Dodge 100 "Kew" trucks) which came out in 1958, had its cab styled by a company called Airflow Streamlines of Northampton after Chrysler contracted them.
[src:commer/commer] Airflow Streamlines was coincidentally the same company that styled the 1955 Superpoise, leading to both vehicles using almost the same cab design and having many parts interchangeable.
[src:commer/commer] For export markets, the 200 series was sold as a Fargo or DeSoto.
[src:commer/commer] The Dodge would go on until 1963, before being modernized as the "Dodge 400 series", receiving the cab of the American Dodge D series medium-duty truck and a new range of engines by Perkins and Leyland Motors.
[src:commer/commer] This model was mostly produced for export but was also available to the United Kingdom.
[src:commer/commer] The model was not successful on its home market and production there would end by 1965.
[src:commer/commer] Due to the Dodge 400 series being almost identical to the original American truck, telling the two apart is not easy.
[src:commer/commer] Dodge would re-use the method of mating an American truck with a European chassis on the Dodge 50 series of 1979, effectively using the Dodge B series van cab and a British designed medium-duty truck platform.
[src:commer/commer] Commer produced buses and is recorded as delivering four to Widnes in 1909.
[src:commer/commer] The Commando was released after the Second World War, and the Avenger on 28 February 1948, fitted with the TS3 engine from 1954.
[src:commer/commer] The Commando was used as a Crew Bus by the Royal Air Force following the Second World War with a 1 1/2 Length Observation deck.
[src:commer/commer] The Commer 8 cwt was a light commercial vehicle produced by Commer during the 1930s, competing in the 8 long cwt (410 kg) van range.
[src:commer/commer] It had a four-cylinder engine with 1185 cc.
[src:commer/commer] The bore was 63 mm and the stroke was 95 mm.
[src:commer/commer] The maximum power was 33 hp at 4100 rpm.
[src:commer/commer] The Commer Light Pick-Up was a pickup truck based on the Hillman Minx saloon and produced by Commer during the 1950s; a similar Hillman-badged model was also produced.
[src:commer/commer] The Mark III was powered by a 1,184 cc (72.3 cu in) four-cylinder engine, the Mark VI by a 1,265 cc (77.2 cu in) unit and the Mark VIII by a 1,390 cc (85 cu in) engine.
[src:commer/commer] Australian production circa 1950 included a coupé utility variant with an additional side window.
[src:commer/commer] The Commer Express Delivery Van was a light commercial vehicle produced by Commer during the 1950s, competing in the 8–10 long cwt (410–510 kg) van range.
[src:commer/commer] It was based on the Hillman Minx saloon and evolved in parallel with that model, with designations ranging from Mark III to Mark VIIIB.
[src:commer/commer] The 1957 model, which featured a load space of 100 cu ft (2.8 m3) and a payload of approximately 9 cwt, was powered by a 1,390 cc (85 cu in) four-cylinder Hillman engine and was fitted with a four-speed column-change gearbox.
[src:commer/commer] It had coil-sprung independent front suspension and drum brakes all round with twin-leading-shoe units at the front.
[src:commer/commer] The Commer Cob is a 7 cwt delivery van introduced in early 1956 based on the Hillman Husky, itself a derivative of the Hillman Minx Mark VIII.
[src:commer/commer] Although similar to the *Express* it was shorter overall with a smaller payload area and a more rounded design.
[src:commer/commer] In 1958 new Cob and Husky models were introduced, based on the "Audax" Hillman Minx.
[src:commer/commer] The Commer Imp Van was introduced in September 1965 and was based on the Hillman Imp saloon.
[src:commer/commer] It was renamed as the Hillman Imp Van in October 1968, with total production reaching 18,194 units prior to it being phased out in July 1970.
[src:commer/commer] The last generation of the Hillman Husky estate car, which was introduced in July 1967, was based on the Imp Van and used the same sheetmetal ahead of the B-pillar.
[src:commer/commer] The Commer BF/B was a light/medium duty van produced by Commer from 1957, with a design similar to that of the present step-van.
[src:commer/commer] Many examples of these vans were coach-built as ice cream vans and ambulances.
[src:commer/commer] A number of chassis cab versions were also produced but most of these went for export to countries such as Hong Kong and Sweden, where they were sometimes converted as pickup trucks and box trucks with local bodywork and some other modifications.
[src:commer/commer] It had a 1.5 long tons (1.5 tonnes) payload and was fitted with a 2267 cc Straight-4 ohv Humber Hawk engine alongside the transmission.
[src:commer/commer] A diesel version of the same engine was also available.
[src:commer/commer] Production ended in 1966 after Commer had launched the newer Walk-Thru in 1961, leading to the BF being offered as a cheaper alternative to what eventually became its successor.
[src:commer/commer] Due to the relation between Commer and Karrier at the time, a rebadged version of the BF was also built and sold by Karrier.
[src:commer/commer] The Commer Walk-Thru was introduced in 1961 as a replacement for the Commer BF.
[src:commer/commer] The Walk-Thru was offered in 1+1⁄2-ton, 2-ton and 3-ton van and cab-chassis variants with a choice of diesel or petrol engines.
[src:commer/commer] This van was also built in Spain by Santana Motors, beginning in 1964.
[src:commer/commer] Todd Motors in Petone, New Zealand, made a short run of these vehicles during 1970, however they were not a successful model.
[src:commer/commer] The body sides were flat steel, pop riveted to the steel sides.
[src:commer/commer] The Walk-Thru was later modernized and sold under the Dodge brand (parent company Renault / Chrysler) until the late 1970s when it was replaced by the 50 Series of commercial vehicles.
[src:commer/commer] The Commer FC was introduced in 1960 with many body styles, including a 1,500 cc (92 cu in) van.
[src:commer/commer] After engine and interior upgrades it was renamed the PB in 1967 and the *SpaceVan* in 1974.
[src:commer/commer] As noted above, it would be sold as a Dodge and Fargo model until 1976, when both Commer and Fargo names were dropped.
[src:commer/commer] These were rounded-front forward-control vans with narrow front track—a legacy of their Humber car-derived suspension.
[src:commer/commer] Using at first the Hillman-derived 1,500 cc (92 cu in) 4-cylinder engine in the PA series, then the larger 1,600 cc (98 cu in), and from 1968 onwards the 1,725 cc (105.3 cu in) unit in the PB, only the cast-iron-head version of this engine were used.
[src:commer/commer] A Perkins 4108 diesel was also available.
[src:commer/commer] Reportedly, one condition of the government bailout of Chrysler's British operations in 1976 was a commitment to upgrade the Spacevan, which was praised for its brakes, cornering, and price, but criticized for its power, comforts, and top speed.
[src:commer/commer] A revised Spacevan was thus introduced in 1977, using the same mechanicals but with numerous cosmetic changes, conveniences, and a new interior.
[src:commer/commer] Although outdated by its demise in 1982, by which time Commer had been taken over by Peugeot, the Spacevan remained a familiar sight in the UK thanks to its role with Post Office Telecommunications—which was almost solely responsible for it remaining in production for so long.
[src:commer/commer] These vans and outstanding orders were inherited by British Telecom on its formation in October 1981.
[src:commer/commer] By this time, there were three engines: two 1.7-litre petrol engines of 37 kW (with low compression) and 42 kW (with high compression), and a small diesel engine (31 kW), with a four-speed manual transmission and no automatic available.
[src:commer/commer] Commer made a range of military vehicles for use during the Second World War, with the range still in use in the 1980s.
[src:commer/commer] Commer designed and manufactured its own diesel engines for its heavy commercial vehicles and buses.
[src:commer/commer] They were low-profile units designed to be deployed under the floor of the cab.
[src:commer/commer] The TS3 engine was a two-stroke diesel unit with three cylinders each containing a pair of pistons arranged with the combustion chamber formed between the crown of the piston pair and the cylinder walls.
[src:commer/commer] It was designed specifically for the Commer range of trucks.
[src:commer/commer] The TS3 and derivative TS4 were unique in using rockers to deliver power to the single crankshaft.
[src:commer/commer] The TS4 engine ran 1.2 million miles as a pre-production prototype.
[src:commer/commer] The Scottish motor racing team Ecurie Ecosse, used a Commer-based double-deck transporter during the 1950s.
[src:commer/commer] Commer acquired the Karrier company in 1934 and Karrier joined the Rootes Group.
[src:commer/commer] Special products in their catalogue included their *Cob* tractor, their "mechanical horse" originated by Karrier in 1930, and municipal motor appliances: refuse collectors, sweepers and trolley buses.
[src:commer/commer] The *Cob* had been supplied to the Southern, LNE and LM&S railway companies and repeat orders were in hand at the time Karrier was bought.
[src:commer/commer] In the early 1960s production moved to Dunstable where Commer, Dodge (UK) and Karrier were all brought together.
[src:commer/commer] The Karrier trademark is now owned by Peugeot.
